1. The Document Structure

    <!DOCTYPE html> & <html>
        Definition: The universal declaration that tells the browser this file is a modern web page.

        Usage: It wraps the entire document. Every other piece of code lives inside the <html> boundaries.

    <head>
        Definition: The invisible control center of the page. Nothing inside here shows up directly on the screen.

        Usage: Holds settings, titles, and links to external design files.

    <meta>
        Definition: Hidden tags that provide background instructions to the web browser.

        Usage: Used here to ensure the text characters display correctly (utf-8) and to force
                the page to scale and fit properly on mobile phone screens (viewport).

    <link>
        Definition: A bridge connecting the current HTML file to an external styling document.

        Usage: Used specifically to pull in the Bootstrap CSS framework from the internet,
                instantly applying professional styling, margins, and colors to the raw HTML elements.

2. The Visible Canvas

    <body>
        Definition: The main container for all visible content.

        Usage: Everything intended to be seen on the screen is placed inside here.

    <div>
        Definition: A division or an invisible rectangular box.

        Usage: The most heavily used element in the code. It acts as a structural frame.
                Combined with Bootstrap classes (like container, form-group, alert),
                it strictly controls spacing, stacking, and alignment of the form items.

    <h1>
        Definition: The largest, most important text heading on the page.

        Usage: Displays the main title, "Job Application Form", at the very top of the structure.

    <br>
        Definition: A simple line break.

        Usage: Forces whatever comes next to drop down to a brand new line.

3. The Data Engine (The Form)

    <form>
        Definition: The interactive wrapper that specifically gathers user input and sends it to a server.

        Usage: Configured with method="post". This acts as a secure shipping container,
                ensuring the typed data is sent securely to the Python backend in the background,
                rather than exposing it in the web address bar.

    <label>
        Definition: A piece of text directly attached to a specific input box.

        Usage: Tells the user exactly what to type. For the radio buttons, it is linked via the for attribute,
                meaning a click on the text itself will activate the associated circular button.

    <input>
        Definition: The actual interactive field where data is collected.

        Usage: Modified heavily using the type attribute:

    type="text" & type="email": Creates typing boxes.

    type="date": Forces a calendar popup for date selection.

    type="radio": Creates circular buttons where only one option can be chosen.

    Crucial backend link: The name attribute in these inputs (e.g., name="first_name") is the exact key
            the Python backend uses to extract the data.

    <button>
        Definition: A physical, clickable trigger.

        Usage: Configured with type="submit". Clicking it commands the <form> to instantly pack up
                all collected data and shoot it to the Python server.

4. The Dynamic & External Logic

    {% ... %} and {{ ... }} (Jinja2 Templating)
        Definition: Not actual HTML. This is a special templating language that Python understands.

        Usage: Allows the backend server to inject dynamic variables (like the success flash message) directly
                into the static HTML before the page is ever sent to the browser.

    <script>
        Definition: A tag used to embed or link executable JavaScript code.

        Usage: Placed at the absolute bottom of the <body> to load external logic (jQuery and Bootstrap JS)
                from the internet, allowing advanced interactive UI features to work properly without slowing
                down the initial page load.